1
00:00:26,327 --> 00:00:27,304
Did you catch her?

2
00:00:27,328 --> 00:00:28,705
Oh, yes. I caught her.

3
00:00:28,729 --> 00:00:30,607
But once she starts
writing, she can't stop.

4
00:00:30,631 --> 00:00:31,908
Heaven forbid.

5
00:00:31,932 --> 00:00:34,211
I should have jammed that
pen into her carotid artery.

6
00:00:34,235 --> 00:00:37,747
Mm. I think they double
the fine once you draw blood.

7
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:40,484
You need a building
with guest parking.

8
00:00:40,508 --> 00:00:42,152
Take my spot.

9
00:00:42,176 --> 00:00:43,775
I don't want your spot.

10
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:47,924
Damn!

11
00:00:47,948 --> 00:00:50,193
What?

12
00:00:50,217 --> 00:00:51,217
No milk.

13
00:00:52,870 --> 00:00:54,263
Want some of mine?

14
00:00:54,287 --> 00:00:56,166
A grown man, you put
an empty milk carton

15
00:00:56,190 --> 00:00:57,350
back into the refrigerator.

16
00:00:57,374 --> 00:00:59,357
It's not empty.

17
00:01:02,813 --> 00:01:04,440
Now it's empty.

18
00:01:04,464 --> 00:01:05,875
Not that it chills anything

19
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:08,000
cooler than room
temperature anyway.

20
00:01:09,069 --> 00:01:10,246
It's just a parking ticket.

21
00:01:10,270 --> 00:01:11,681
It's not just the ticket.

22
00:01:11,705 --> 00:01:13,316
It's that had to go
chasing down there

23
00:01:13,340 --> 00:01:15,085
half-dressed with my hair wet.

24
00:01:15,109 --> 00:01:16,937
I said I'd go. But
you didn't, did you?

25
00:01:16,961 --> 00:01:18,405
You didn't give me a chance.

26
00:01:18,429 --> 00:01:19,472
You weren't fast enough!

27
00:01:21,364 --> 00:01:22,709
I'll pay the ticket. Okay?

28
00:01:22,733 --> 00:01:24,477
Calm down.

29
00:01:24,501 --> 00:01:26,200
I paid the other ones.

30
00:01:30,941 --> 00:01:32,373
What?

31
00:01:35,246 --> 00:01:37,290
Let's just say it
wasn't your first ticket.

32
00:01:37,314 --> 00:01:40,127
You stole parking
tickets off my windshield?

33
00:01:40,151 --> 00:01:42,129
Just two. And paid
without telling me?

34
00:01:42,153 --> 00:01:44,948
Well, I was trying
to avoid... this.

35
00:01:44,972 --> 00:01:47,633
Well, that's it then. I'm
not staying here anymore.

36
00:01:47,657 --> 00:01:48,768
Here we go.

37
00:01:48,792 --> 00:01:51,204
Every faucet leaks.
Your toilet actually rocks.

38
00:01:51,228 --> 00:01:52,272
I kinda like that.

39
00:01:52,296 --> 00:01:54,174
There are creatures
scurrying in the walls.

40
00:01:54,198 --> 00:01:56,909
Do you know what scurries
about in walls, Mark?

41
00:01:56,933 --> 00:01:58,066
Bunnies?

42
00:02:00,103 --> 00:02:02,315
Do you wanna take the
El train, or shall we drive?

43
00:02:10,580 --> 00:02:11,858
Hey, is this the AA meeting?

44
00:02:11,882 --> 00:02:13,159
How'd you guess?

45
00:02:13,183 --> 00:02:15,028
I'm Brant. What's your
name? Hi, I'm John.

46
00:02:15,052 --> 00:02:17,780
Ah, thanks, John. Welcome.

47
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:20,049
To believe a power
greater than ourselves

48
00:02:20,073 --> 00:02:22,085
could restore us to sanity.

49
00:02:22,109 --> 00:02:25,255
Step Three: Made a
decision to turn our will...

50
00:02:25,279 --> 00:02:26,256
It's a lot of coffee.

51
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:28,391
This is backup.

52
00:02:28,415 --> 00:02:30,227
First time? Here? Yeah.

53
00:02:30,251 --> 00:02:31,861
It's a good group.

54
00:02:31,885 --> 00:02:35,565
A searching and fearless
moral inventory of ourselves.

55
00:02:35,589 --> 00:02:39,001
Step Five: Admitted
to God, to ourselves,

56
00:02:39,025 --> 00:02:42,294
and to another human being
the exact nature of our wrongs.

57
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:47,043
Step Six: Were entirely
ready to have God

58
00:02:47,067 --> 00:02:50,230
remove all of these
defects of character.

59
00:02:50,254 --> 00:02:54,950
Step Seven: Humbly asked
him to remove our shortcomings.

60
00:02:54,974 --> 00:02:59,873
Step Eight: Made a list of all
persons whom we have harmed

61
00:02:59,897 --> 00:03:03,309
and became willing to
make amends to them all.

62
00:03:03,333 --> 00:03:05,695
Step Nine: Made direct amends

63
00:03:05,719 --> 00:03:07,730
to such people wherever possible

64
00:03:07,754 --> 00:03:10,700
except when to do so
would harm them or others.

65
00:04:02,309 --> 00:04:04,921
Doc, can you take this
guy? He is driving me crazy.

66
00:04:04,945 --> 00:04:06,622
Same here. Oh, no.

67
00:04:06,646 --> 00:04:07,657
Shunt's clotted.

68
00:04:07,681 --> 00:04:09,325
He missed his
dialysis appointment.

69
00:04:09,349 --> 00:04:11,795
Mr. Fletcher, only
one day late, huh?

70
00:04:11,819 --> 00:04:13,830
You? No, not you. You know him?

71
00:04:13,854 --> 00:04:15,198
Yeah, he's one of our favorites.

72
00:04:15,222 --> 00:04:20,103
Hey, Cleo? Can you, uh,
take Mr. Fletcher, please?

73
00:04:20,127 --> 00:04:22,038
I see you called 911 again.

74
00:04:22,062 --> 00:04:24,357
They're faster
than the El train.

75
00:04:24,381 --> 00:04:25,725
My arm stopped buzzing.

76
00:04:25,749 --> 00:04:27,360
No thrill, no bruit.

77
00:04:27,384 --> 00:04:28,683
Talk English.

78
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:31,330
Mark, ready?

79
00:04:31,354 --> 00:04:32,499
In a second.

80
00:04:32,523 --> 00:04:33,833
Raise your right foot.

81
00:04:33,857 --> 00:04:34,918
I can't.

82
00:04:34,942 --> 00:04:36,469
I don't want to
keep him waiting.

83
00:04:36,493 --> 00:04:37,625
I'll be right there.

84
00:04:38,411 --> 00:04:39,494
Okay.

85
00:04:40,647 --> 00:04:42,525
Have you started
teaching rounds?

86
00:04:42,549 --> 00:04:44,127
No. The residents
are waiting in ICU.

87
00:04:44,151 --> 00:04:45,361
All right, I'll be there.

88
00:04:45,385 --> 00:04:47,897
And you need to schedule
the Surgical Service meeting.

89
00:04:47,921 --> 00:04:49,599
Tomorrow. You have a mastectomy.

90
00:04:49,623 --> 00:04:50,600
Well, whenever.

91
00:04:50,624 --> 00:04:52,668
Dr. Benton.

92
00:04:52,692 --> 00:04:54,788
Hey, Carter. What
are you doing here?

93
00:04:54,812 --> 00:04:56,056
I have a meeting.

94
00:04:56,080 --> 00:04:57,824
Oh, right. Hi, Shirley.

95
00:04:57,848 --> 00:04:58,825
Hi, Dr. Carter.

96
00:04:58,849 --> 00:05:00,059
I need you to sign off

97
00:05:00,083 --> 00:05:02,345
on last month's O.R.
expenditure report.

98
00:05:02,369 --> 00:05:03,346
I've never done that.

99
00:05:03,370 --> 00:05:04,547
You do now. I take care of it.

100
00:05:04,571 --> 00:05:06,488
You just sign it.

101
00:05:07,641 --> 00:05:09,418
Suit yourself. I need it by 4.

102
00:05:09,442 --> 00:05:11,175
It's good to see you, Carter.

103
00:05:13,881 --> 00:05:15,346
Important Attending stuff?

104
00:05:16,749 --> 00:05:18,494
Oh, yeah, well. Congratulations.

105
00:05:18,518 --> 00:05:21,214
Thanks. Ah, man, you look good.

106
00:05:21,238 --> 00:05:24,551
Well, couldn't look much worse
than the last time you saw me.

107
00:05:24,575 --> 00:05:26,335
He's gotten big.

108
00:05:26,359 --> 00:05:27,354
Yeah.

109
00:05:27,378 --> 00:05:28,755
Hi, Reece.

110
00:05:28,779 --> 00:05:30,329
Hey.

111
00:05:33,199 --> 00:05:34,365
Well, hey, you're in a hurry.

112
00:05:36,035 --> 00:05:38,865
Yeah. Um, I'll see
you later, all right?

113
00:05:38,889 --> 00:05:41,201
I don't know. Maybe. We'll see.

114
00:05:41,225 --> 00:05:43,758
Ah, good luck, Carter.

115
00:05:47,631 --> 00:05:49,091
<i>When does he wanna start?</i>

116
00:05:49,115 --> 00:05:50,126
As soon as possible.

117
00:05:50,150 --> 00:05:51,527
I don't think
that's a good idea.

118
00:05:51,551 --> 00:05:53,830
62-year-old female,
slurred speech,

119
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:55,397
also weak grip
in her right hand.

120
00:05:55,421 --> 00:05:56,633
Any history of stroke?

121
00:05:56,657 --> 00:05:58,200
Yes. A lacunar infarct.

122
00:05:58,224 --> 00:05:59,568
She got much worse this morning.

123
00:05:59,592 --> 00:06:00,837
He's eager to get back to work.

124
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:02,338
So we just throw
him in the deep end?

125
00:06:02,362 --> 00:06:03,773
No. Of course not.

126
00:06:03,797 --> 00:06:06,375
We'll start him on half-shifts,
limited responsibilities.

127
00:06:06,399 --> 00:06:08,244
In the same place
where he started using.

128
00:06:08,268 --> 00:06:10,046
Mark, he's doing the
program every day.

129
00:06:10,070 --> 00:06:12,649
Good. Make him take
time. He can afford it.

130
00:06:12,673 --> 00:06:14,717
Okay. We'll
monitor his progress,

131
00:06:14,741 --> 00:06:17,120
and if he gets into
trouble, we'll just cut back.

132
00:06:17,144 --> 00:06:19,989
If he gets into
trouble, it's too late.

133
00:06:20,013 --> 00:06:21,056
Please, somebody!

134
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:22,825
What is it? I'm
having contractions!

135
00:06:22,849 --> 00:06:24,727
Are you pregnant? Only 22 weeks.

136
00:06:24,751 --> 00:06:26,762
Come here. Try to relax, okay?

137
00:06:26,786 --> 00:06:28,285
Here, you're gonna sit down.

138
00:06:29,689 --> 00:06:32,123
Sit here. Wait one second, okay?

139
00:06:33,326 --> 00:06:36,639
Dr. Chen, I need you
over here. No, now.

140
00:06:36,663 --> 00:06:37,640
How did you get here?

141
00:06:37,664 --> 00:06:39,675
Taxi. I was shopping downtown.

142
00:06:39,699 --> 00:06:41,644
What is it? She's
having contractions.

143
00:06:41,668 --> 00:06:42,778
How far along are you?

144
00:06:42,802 --> 00:06:44,747
Twenty-two weeks.
Oh, that's too early.

145
00:06:44,771 --> 00:06:46,448
You're probably
having what are called

146
00:06:46,472 --> 00:06:48,250
Braxton Hicks contractions.

147
00:06:48,274 --> 00:06:50,887
They're coming
every three minutes.

148
00:06:50,911 --> 00:06:52,522
Get a gurney,
clear a trauma room,

149
00:06:52,546 --> 00:06:54,857
start an IV and call OB. Okay.

150
00:06:54,881 --> 00:06:56,325
What's your name? Regina.

151
00:06:56,349 --> 00:06:58,193
Okay, Regina, don't push.

152
00:06:58,217 --> 00:07:02,482
Whatever you do,
don't push. Okay?

153
00:07:04,007 --> 00:07:05,068
How much?

154
00:07:05,092 --> 00:07:06,202
Four, almost 5.

155
00:07:06,226 --> 00:07:07,236
No, that can't be right.

156
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:09,905
I was 4 centimeters
two hours ago.

157
00:07:09,929 --> 00:07:10,906
You're doing fine.

158
00:07:10,930 --> 00:07:12,542
Can Dr. Coburn take a look?

159
00:07:12,566 --> 00:07:14,643
She was called in
to do a C-section.

160
00:07:14,667 --> 00:07:15,628
How long will that take?

161
00:07:15,652 --> 00:07:17,229
We have plenty of time.

162
00:07:17,253 --> 00:07:19,031
Why don't we roll
you back on your side

163
00:07:19,055 --> 00:07:20,588
and get you more comfortable.

164
00:07:21,958 --> 00:07:24,387
Abby, they need
someone downstairs.

165
00:07:24,411 --> 00:07:25,388
Where?

166
00:07:25,412 --> 00:07:27,723
ER. They have a preterm labor.

167
00:07:27,747 --> 00:07:28,758
Get a resident.

168
00:07:28,782 --> 00:07:30,310
Simons and Perry are delivering.

169
00:07:30,334 --> 00:07:32,512
Lift your leg. Where's Dana?

170
00:07:32,536 --> 00:07:34,481
She's on break. Not
back for another five.

171
00:07:34,505 --> 00:07:36,182
You're not leaving, are you?

172
00:07:36,206 --> 00:07:37,354
It sounded urgent.

173
00:07:38,876 --> 00:07:40,353
Do you know where you are?

174
00:07:44,965 --> 00:07:46,659
Let the doctor
check you out first.

175
00:07:46,683 --> 00:07:47,676
What did she say?

176
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:48,678
She wants to go home.

177
00:07:48,702 --> 00:07:49,862
Pulse ox is 92.

178
00:07:52,506 --> 00:07:54,050
She's in A-fib.

179
00:07:54,074 --> 00:07:56,352
It probably triggered
the new stroke.

180
00:07:56,376 --> 00:07:57,921
Do you provide 24-hour care?

181
00:07:57,945 --> 00:07:59,322
Yes.

182
00:07:59,346 --> 00:08:00,790
Does she have any family?

183
00:08:00,814 --> 00:08:03,492
No. Not that she's
in contact with.

184
00:08:03,516 --> 00:08:04,627
Connie, call Psych.

185
00:08:04,651 --> 00:08:05,651
Psych?

186
00:08:06,836 --> 00:08:08,714
After this stoke, she
might not be competent

187
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:10,689
to make her own
medical decisions.

188
00:08:14,994 --> 00:08:17,307
Preterm labor? Next door.

189
00:08:17,331 --> 00:08:21,561
EKG, Chem-7, UA, culture
urine, blood and sputum.

190
00:08:21,585 --> 00:08:23,496
Your husband's on his way, okay?

191
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:24,497
Okay. How far along?

192
00:08:24,521 --> 00:08:25,698
Twenty-two weeks.

193
00:08:25,722 --> 00:08:27,000
Let's hope it's a couple more.

194
00:08:27,024 --> 00:08:29,268
Stop it. Please, stop it!

195
00:08:29,292 --> 00:08:30,269
Where's the resident?

196
00:08:30,293 --> 00:08:31,738
You got me instead.

197
00:08:31,762 --> 00:08:34,007
Membranes are intact,
but she's fully effaced

198
00:08:34,031 --> 00:08:36,075
and dilated to 6 centimeters.

199
00:08:36,099 --> 00:08:38,244
Can you stop it?

200
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:39,846
What's...? What's
her name? Regina.

201
00:08:39,870 --> 00:08:41,581
Regina, did you
have any ultrasounds

202
00:08:41,605 --> 00:08:42,682
during your pregnancy?

203
00:08:42,706 --> 00:08:43,716
About a month ago.

204
00:08:43,740 --> 00:08:45,284
My doctor said
everything was okay.

205
00:08:45,308 --> 00:08:46,302
Who's your doctor?

206
00:08:46,326 --> 00:08:48,171
He's in Indianapolis.

207
00:08:48,195 --> 00:08:50,005
Why is this happening?

208
00:08:50,029 --> 00:08:53,609
Sometimes women go into
preterm labor for no apparent reason.

209
00:08:53,633 --> 00:08:56,312
I shouldn't have come. I
should have stayed home.

210
00:08:56,336 --> 00:08:59,566
This is not your
fault. This happens.

211
00:08:59,590 --> 00:09:01,434
Giving you medicine
to stop contractions.

212
00:09:01,458 --> 00:09:04,437
Your membranes haven't
ruptured yet, which is a good sign.

213
00:09:04,461 --> 00:09:07,039
We're giving you something to
help your baby's lungs mature.

214
00:09:07,063 --> 00:09:08,691
Oh, no! I feel pressure.

215
00:09:12,235 --> 00:09:13,462
Strong contraction.

216
00:09:13,486 --> 00:09:15,164
She's leaking amniotic fluid.

217
00:09:15,188 --> 00:09:16,715
Make them stop. It's too early.

218
00:09:16,739 --> 00:09:18,450
Two grams of amp.

219
00:09:18,474 --> 00:09:20,370
Get a baby warmer in here.

220
00:09:20,394 --> 00:09:22,510
No! It's too early!

221
00:09:32,221 --> 00:09:33,499
Random urine tests.

222
00:09:33,523 --> 00:09:34,722
Yes.

223
00:09:36,660 --> 00:09:38,721
And I get to pay
for them too, I see.

224
00:09:38,745 --> 00:09:40,023
Is that a problem?

225
00:09:40,047 --> 00:09:41,829
No.

226
00:09:43,232 --> 00:09:45,044
In addition to the
state meetings

227
00:09:45,068 --> 00:09:47,914
we'll require 90
NA or AA meetings

228
00:09:47,938 --> 00:09:49,615
during the first 90 days.

229
00:09:49,639 --> 00:09:52,035
That's not a problem.
I'm going anyway.

230
00:09:52,059 --> 00:09:53,302
Good. Good.

231
00:09:53,326 --> 00:09:54,988
And the three of us
will meet once a week

232
00:09:55,012 --> 00:09:57,122
just to, you know, check in.

233
00:09:57,146 --> 00:09:59,475
Make sure you're
handling the stress.

234
00:09:59,499 --> 00:10:00,499
Okay.

235
00:10:02,919 --> 00:10:04,219
I came prepared.

236
00:10:05,222 --> 00:10:06,883
The naltrexone
binds to your opiate...

237
00:10:06,907 --> 00:10:08,322
I know what it does.

238
00:10:11,862 --> 00:10:14,957
It protects you. It blocks
the euphoric effects.

239
00:10:14,981 --> 00:10:16,731
It protects all of us.

240
00:10:21,755 --> 00:10:23,483
You need to, uh, begin today

241
00:10:23,507 --> 00:10:25,940
if you wanna begin
work next week.

242
00:10:33,283 --> 00:10:34,911
You want me to
take it in front of you?

243
00:10:34,935 --> 00:10:38,503
Yeah, we'll periodically
monitor your regimen.

244
00:10:40,774 --> 00:10:41,751
How much?

245
00:10:41,775 --> 00:10:43,674
Fifty milligrams a day.

246
00:10:55,021 --> 00:10:56,599
Sorry. That was, um...

247
00:10:56,623 --> 00:10:57,634
It's okay.

248
00:10:57,658 --> 00:11:00,085
It's gonna be
difficult at first.

249
00:11:00,109 --> 00:11:01,149
So we'll work it out.

250
00:11:03,046 --> 00:11:06,158
All right. So we'll put you on
the schedule for next week.

251
00:11:06,182 --> 00:11:08,728
Tuesday. Start out very light.

252
00:11:08,752 --> 00:11:09,779
No trauma.

253
00:11:09,803 --> 00:11:11,447
Whatever you say.

254
00:11:12,472 --> 00:11:14,616
Kerry, I gotta go. Yeah.

255
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:16,452
See you next week,
Carter. Welcome back.

256
00:11:16,476 --> 00:11:18,175
Thank you.

257
00:11:19,129 --> 00:11:20,206
Thank you both.

258
00:11:20,230 --> 00:11:21,963
Sure thing.

259
00:11:29,940 --> 00:11:32,751
Baby's cephalic. Normal anatomy.

260
00:11:32,775 --> 00:11:33,752
Progressed to 8.

261
00:11:33,776 --> 00:11:35,554
Oh, God, please stop it.

262
00:11:35,578 --> 00:11:36,555
Father's here.

263
00:11:36,579 --> 00:11:38,490
Regina, wh...? What happened?

264
00:11:38,514 --> 00:11:40,292
I was at the mall.
It started hurting.

265
00:11:40,316 --> 00:11:41,978
I... I didn't know what to do.

266
00:11:42,002 --> 00:11:43,896
Is she in labor? Yes.

267
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:45,164
My water broke.

268
00:11:45,188 --> 00:11:48,267
Her OB confirms previous
ultrasounds put her at 21 weeks.

269
00:11:48,291 --> 00:11:49,852
That's way too soon, right?

270
00:11:49,876 --> 00:11:51,220
She's got rales.

271
00:11:51,244 --> 00:11:52,905
Pulmonary edema.
No more terbutaline.

272
00:11:52,929 --> 00:11:54,306
What...? What's wrong?

273
00:11:54,330 --> 00:11:55,707
The medication we're giving you

274
00:11:55,731 --> 00:11:57,509
is causing your
lungs to fill with fluid.

275
00:11:57,533 --> 00:11:59,945
I don't care. Stop
the contractions.

276
00:11:59,969 --> 00:12:01,063
I can't have this baby.

277
00:12:01,087 --> 00:12:03,700
Okay, I'll try 50
mgs of indomethacin.

278
00:12:03,724 --> 00:12:05,724
If the baby's born
now, can it survive?

279
00:12:06,393 --> 00:12:07,369
Joseph, it's coming!

280
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:08,671
The baby's crowning.

281
00:12:08,695 --> 00:12:11,007
Regina, you're gonna
deliver this baby.

282
00:12:11,031 --> 00:12:12,008
No! No!

283
00:12:12,032 --> 00:12:14,594
Yes. There's nothing
else we can do.

284
00:12:14,618 --> 00:12:16,629
What have we got?
Preemie. Under 22 weeks.

285
00:12:16,653 --> 00:12:18,030
Okay. Regina, go ahead and push.

286
00:12:18,054 --> 00:12:19,798
No! No!

287
00:12:19,822 --> 00:12:21,718
You okay there, Dr. Chen? Mm-hm.

288
00:12:21,742 --> 00:12:24,187
The head's out. Whoa.

289
00:12:24,211 --> 00:12:25,388
Oh, my God! Oh, my God!

290
00:12:25,412 --> 00:12:26,973
It's a boy. Is he breathing?

291
00:12:26,997 --> 00:12:28,841
Yes, he's breathing.

292
00:12:28,865 --> 00:12:31,010
Can someone...? Can
someone please help me?

293
00:12:31,034 --> 00:12:32,028
You okay?

294
00:12:32,052 --> 00:12:33,295
Dilute it in 1000 cc's,

295
00:12:33,319 --> 00:12:34,597
100 drops per minute.

296
00:12:34,621 --> 00:12:36,498
I don't hear
anything. Is he alive?

297
00:12:36,522 --> 00:12:37,633
Yes.

298
00:12:37,657 --> 00:12:39,757
Let's get a weight.

299
00:12:41,194 --> 00:12:42,171
He's so little.

300
00:12:42,195 --> 00:12:44,040
BP, 100/60.

301
00:12:44,064 --> 00:12:46,542
Okay. Let's give
the mom 40 of Lasix.

302
00:12:46,566 --> 00:12:47,743
Take her temp.

303
00:12:47,767 --> 00:12:51,636
Please save him.
Please save my baby.

304
00:13:00,530 --> 00:13:01,863
You're doing charts?

305
00:13:02,866 --> 00:13:04,499
Yeah, I needed to catch up.

306
00:13:08,722 --> 00:13:12,668
Um... Look, I-I'm
really sorry about, um...

307
00:13:12,692 --> 00:13:14,258
With the baby.

308
00:13:15,111 --> 00:13:16,222
It's all right.

309
00:13:16,246 --> 00:13:18,074
Our reactions can
surprise us sometimes.

310
00:13:18,098 --> 00:13:21,466
But you need to go back in
there and manage your patient.

311
00:13:22,402 --> 00:13:25,131
Um... I can't.

312
00:13:25,155 --> 00:13:27,333
Jing-Mei, you should know
you're being considered

313
00:13:27,357 --> 00:13:29,051
for chief resident next year.

314
00:13:29,075 --> 00:13:32,677
People need to be able to
look to you for leadership.

315
00:13:36,348 --> 00:13:37,832
I'm pregnant.

316
00:13:41,220 --> 00:13:43,298
I... I didn't know what to do,

317
00:13:43,322 --> 00:13:48,308
and then eight weeks
became 12, and 12 became 20.

318
00:13:49,628 --> 00:13:52,575
So you're... You're
20 weeks pregnant?

319
00:13:52,599 --> 00:13:54,231
Twenty-two.

320
00:13:57,537 --> 00:14:00,333
You know, that baby
was the size of mine.

321
00:14:00,357 --> 00:14:02,990
Oh, sweetie...

322
00:14:05,895 --> 00:14:09,546
Why did you wait
so long to tell me?

323
00:14:11,750 --> 00:14:14,881
My parents are gonna kill me.

324
00:14:14,905 --> 00:14:16,648
You should go home. No.

325
00:14:16,672 --> 00:14:19,001
Go home. I'll cover
the rest of your shift.

326
00:14:19,025 --> 00:14:23,205
We'll work out your
schedule tomorrow.

327
00:14:23,229 --> 00:14:24,829
Okay.

328
00:14:26,365 --> 00:14:27,645
Good.

329
00:14:28,552 --> 00:14:31,797
Oh. Not fair. Not
in the workplace.

330
00:14:31,821 --> 00:14:33,900
I found a soft spot.
I'm going to exploit it.

331
00:14:33,924 --> 00:14:35,267
I'll exploit you. Mm-hm.

332
00:14:35,291 --> 00:14:36,636
You know I will. Bring it on.

333
00:14:36,660 --> 00:14:37,737
Time and place.

334
00:14:37,761 --> 00:14:39,505
Clotted-off fistula
needs a new shunt.

335
00:14:40,897 --> 00:14:41,874
Renal failure?

336
00:14:41,898 --> 00:14:43,709
Missed his dialysis.

337
00:14:43,733 --> 00:14:45,077
Mr. Fletcher? Who else?

338
00:14:45,101 --> 00:14:46,178
Give him to somebody else.

339
00:14:46,202 --> 00:14:47,380
I got stuck with him.

340
00:14:47,404 --> 00:14:49,665
Last time, the man
yelled in my stethoscope.

341
00:14:49,689 --> 00:14:51,600
And he grabbed
my ass. Suck it up.

342
00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:54,136
Uh-uh. Come on. Be a man.

343
00:14:58,214 --> 00:14:59,892
That's not right.
Oh, you're crying?

344
00:14:59,916 --> 00:15:01,449
That's not right.

345
00:15:02,351 --> 00:15:03,328
You guys got a baby?

346
00:15:03,352 --> 00:15:04,797
Twenty-two-week preemie.

347
00:15:04,821 --> 00:15:05,798
Still breathing?

348
00:15:05,822 --> 00:15:07,232
For now. Oh, man.

349
00:15:07,256 --> 00:15:09,852
What took you so long?
I need to take a dump.

350
00:15:09,876 --> 00:15:12,196
It's good to see you
too, Mr. Fletcher.

351
00:15:12,629 --> 00:15:13,873
Is he hypothermic? Yeah.

352
00:15:13,897 --> 00:15:14,974
Okay. Order another lamp.

353
00:15:14,998 --> 00:15:16,330
It's on its way down.

354
00:15:22,572 --> 00:15:23,816
What's his pulse?

355
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:25,439
Down to 90.

356
00:15:27,611 --> 00:15:29,321
This is some heated saline

357
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:32,947
to keep him warm
while you hold him.

358
00:15:34,985 --> 00:15:36,012
Did your husband leave?

359
00:15:36,036 --> 00:15:38,965
He went to call a priest.

360
00:15:38,989 --> 00:15:41,922
We wanna baptize our baby.

361
00:15:43,626 --> 00:15:46,205
Well, there's a priest
on call with the hospital,

362
00:15:46,229 --> 00:15:48,024
unless you had
someone specific in mind.

363
00:15:48,048 --> 00:15:52,461
No, we're just in
town for a few days.

364
00:15:52,485 --> 00:15:57,471
My doctor said I could travel
during my second trimester.

365
00:16:00,025 --> 00:16:02,104
Well, Regina, this probably
would have happened

366
00:16:02,128 --> 00:16:05,207
whether you were
traveling or not.

367
00:16:05,231 --> 00:16:08,310
We tried for, um,

368
00:16:08,334 --> 00:16:12,331
almost two years to get
pregnant and finally gave up.

369
00:16:12,355 --> 00:16:16,023
And then suddenly, I was.

370
00:16:18,161 --> 00:16:21,612
Look at him. He's hanging on.

371
00:16:22,932 --> 00:16:28,347
I counted 10 little
fingers and 10 little toes.

372
00:16:28,371 --> 00:16:31,205
He looks perfect.

373
00:16:32,975 --> 00:16:36,160
He's just a little small.

374
00:16:41,967 --> 00:16:43,912
Even if your baby
was a few weeks older

375
00:16:43,936 --> 00:16:45,847
and somehow
managed to survive...

376
00:16:45,871 --> 00:16:49,785
I know that that's what you say
because that's what you've seen,

377
00:16:49,809 --> 00:16:53,811
but maybe he's
meant to be a miracle.

378
00:16:55,214 --> 00:16:57,848
Sometimes you have
to help a miracle along.

379
00:17:00,853 --> 00:17:04,433
And sometimes
you have to let go.

380
00:17:04,457 --> 00:17:05,600
What took so long?

381
00:17:05,624 --> 00:17:07,369
They had eight of us
in a holding pattern.

382
00:17:07,393 --> 00:17:08,370
Are we still in Trauma 1?

383
00:17:08,394 --> 00:17:09,394
Yeah, sure.

384
00:17:11,230 --> 00:17:12,908
How bad is it?

385
00:17:12,932 --> 00:17:15,411
I'm not sure I should
discuss this with you.

386
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:16,745
Why?

387
00:17:16,769 --> 00:17:18,247
I can't share
medical information

388
00:17:18,271 --> 00:17:20,199
with anyone but a family member.

389
00:17:20,223 --> 00:17:21,701
Glenda and I are family.

390
00:17:21,725 --> 00:17:23,002
I thought you were her nurse.

391
00:17:23,026 --> 00:17:25,209
No, I'm, uh...

392
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:29,709
We're partners.

393
00:17:29,733 --> 00:17:32,266
Oh. Right.

394
00:17:33,569 --> 00:17:35,937
We should sit down.

395
00:17:41,845 --> 00:17:42,955
Hey.

396
00:17:42,979 --> 00:17:44,690
You're safe. I've had my coffee.

397
00:17:44,714 --> 00:17:46,658
Good. How about a date tonight?

398
00:17:46,682 --> 00:17:48,094
Sure. As long as
it's at my place.

399
00:17:48,118 --> 00:17:49,595
I was thinking
the going-out kind.

400
00:17:49,619 --> 00:17:50,696
We're going out Friday.

401
00:17:50,720 --> 00:17:52,564
Yeah, I moved up a reservation.

402
00:17:52,588 --> 00:17:53,565
What reservation?

403
00:17:53,589 --> 00:17:54,934
It's a surprise.

404
00:17:54,958 --> 00:17:55,935
Look, Mark, I'm fine.

405
00:17:55,959 --> 00:17:58,137
I just had an
episode this morning.

406
00:17:58,161 --> 00:17:59,638
I know. I know. I'm used to 'em.

407
00:17:59,662 --> 00:18:02,241
Six o'clock. Trust me.
You'll like the place.

408
00:18:02,265 --> 00:18:05,310
By the way, your patient has
an abscess around L4 and L5.

409
00:18:05,334 --> 00:18:06,578
Who? Patterson.

410
00:18:06,602 --> 00:18:08,914
I was in Radiology
when they flagged his film.

411
00:18:08,938 --> 00:18:10,315
Suddenly bored? What?

412
00:18:10,339 --> 00:18:11,834
Poaching my patients?

413
00:18:11,858 --> 00:18:13,902
There can be some improvement

414
00:18:13,926 --> 00:18:16,205
in the first 24
hours after a stroke.

415
00:18:16,229 --> 00:18:19,542
But in Glenda's case, I'm afraid
there's too much brain damage.

416
00:18:19,566 --> 00:18:20,709
So she'll never recover.

417
00:18:20,733 --> 00:18:22,044
Maybe slightly.

418
00:18:22,068 --> 00:18:23,078
Dr. Kovac?

419
00:18:23,102 --> 00:18:24,863
Her sats are dropping to 86.

420
00:18:24,887 --> 00:18:26,164
Glenda? Yes.

421
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:27,232
What does that mean?

422
00:18:27,256 --> 00:18:29,468
She's not getting enough oxygen.

423
00:18:32,361 --> 00:18:34,205
Eight ET tube, 10 cc syringe.

424
00:18:34,229 --> 00:18:36,909
BP's 110/90. Pulse is 110.

425
00:18:36,933 --> 00:18:38,877
Put her on a 100%
non-rebreather.

426
00:18:38,901 --> 00:18:40,546
This your patient?

427
00:18:40,570 --> 00:18:43,181
Large CVA with
dense hemiparesis.

428
00:18:43,205 --> 00:18:46,118
Chest x-ray shows an
aspiration pneumonia.

429
00:18:46,142 --> 00:18:48,704
Ma'am, we may have to
put a tube down your throat

430
00:18:48,728 --> 00:18:49,728
to help you breathe.

431
00:18:51,931 --> 00:18:53,459
Do you know where you are?

432
00:18:53,483 --> 00:18:55,060
Psych note says
she's not competent.

433
00:18:55,084 --> 00:18:56,295
I think she's just confused.

434
00:18:56,319 --> 00:18:57,896
Does she have an
advance directive?

435
00:18:57,920 --> 00:18:58,897
What do you mean?

436
00:18:58,921 --> 00:19:00,432
Like a "Do Not
Resuscitate" order.

437
00:19:00,456 --> 00:19:03,001
I don't think she'd wanna
be put on a ventilator.

438
00:19:03,025 --> 00:19:05,254
Suction. I'll put
in an oral airway.

439
00:19:05,278 --> 00:19:06,589
Are you a family member?

440
00:19:06,613 --> 00:19:08,424
No, she's her...

441
00:19:08,448 --> 00:19:10,898
They're together.

442
00:19:12,034 --> 00:19:13,312
Do you have power of attorney?

443
00:19:13,336 --> 00:19:15,231
No, I guess I should,
but we didn't do that.

444
00:19:15,255 --> 00:19:16,599
Sats are climbing.

445
00:19:16,623 --> 00:19:19,068
Okay, let's keep her
on 50 liters by mask.

446
00:19:19,092 --> 00:19:21,753
She's okay? For now.

447
00:19:21,777 --> 00:19:24,490
But if the pneumonia progresses
we'll have to intubate her

448
00:19:24,514 --> 00:19:28,293
unless a family
member directs us not to.

449
00:19:28,317 --> 00:19:30,045
Or a spouse?

450
00:19:30,069 --> 00:19:31,735
One recognized by law.

451
00:19:38,611 --> 00:19:39,872
Can you do it by phone?

452
00:19:39,896 --> 00:19:40,973
Yes.

453
00:19:40,997 --> 00:19:43,931
Yes, if you can verify
an out-of-town relative.

454
00:19:44,834 --> 00:19:47,763
She has a brother in Houston.

455
00:19:47,787 --> 00:19:48,964
I've never seen one so small.

456
00:19:48,988 --> 00:19:51,166
You can practically
hold it in one hand.

457
00:19:51,190 --> 00:19:53,469
I delivered a 700-gram
baby in med school.

458
00:19:53,493 --> 00:19:54,703
Had a brain-bleed.

459
00:19:54,727 --> 00:19:55,871
I don't even wanna look.

460
00:19:55,895 --> 00:19:58,006
Randi, can you page
the chaplain on call?

461
00:19:58,030 --> 00:19:59,742
I did. The baby's
father already asked.

462
00:19:59,766 --> 00:20:01,310
He's gonna be a few hours.

463
00:20:01,334 --> 00:20:02,678
Well, we don't have a few hours.

464
00:20:02,702 --> 00:20:04,045
He needs to get here.

465
00:20:04,069 --> 00:20:07,349
Well, he's helping talk down
a jumper from a bridge. I...

466
00:20:07,373 --> 00:20:09,117
Okay. Then start
calling parishes

467
00:20:09,141 --> 00:20:11,253
till you can find someone
who can get over here.

468
00:20:11,277 --> 00:20:12,721
You want me to
cold-call priests?

469
00:20:12,745 --> 00:20:14,556
Yes. Now, please.

470
00:20:14,580 --> 00:20:15,658
Okay.

471
00:20:15,682 --> 00:20:18,059
No, I just need the
coags. Dr. Benton?

472
00:20:18,083 --> 00:20:20,663
I don't care what the computer
says, I'm trying to pre-op him.

473
00:20:20,687 --> 00:20:22,097
Is this about Mr. Fletcher?

474
00:20:22,121 --> 00:20:24,400
Tell you what, when they're
ready, page me, all right?

475
00:20:24,424 --> 00:20:25,834
Thank you.

476
00:20:25,858 --> 00:20:27,836
Maureen Conway,
Financial Services.

477
00:20:27,860 --> 00:20:29,705
We can't admit Mr. Fletcher.

478
00:20:29,729 --> 00:20:30,872
Why not? He's got Medicare.

479
00:20:30,896 --> 00:20:32,841
Which he sold to a bankrupt HMO.

480
00:20:32,865 --> 00:20:34,176
Come on, that's not his fault.

481
00:20:34,200 --> 00:20:36,779
True. But in nine months,
Mr. Fletcher has run up

482
00:20:36,803 --> 00:20:40,382
over $200,000 in avoidable
unrecouped charges.

483
00:20:40,406 --> 00:20:42,050
He needs a new dialysis shunt.

484
00:20:42,074 --> 00:20:44,920
Dr. Romano left strict orders
not to admit these patients.

485
00:20:44,944 --> 00:20:47,122
Now, you can stabilize in
the ER, and then transfer.

486
00:20:47,146 --> 00:20:48,824
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Wait a minute.

487
00:20:48,848 --> 00:20:50,892
Do you have an M.D.
behind your name? No.

488
00:20:50,916 --> 00:20:53,529
Yet you're gonna try to tell
me how to treat my patients?

489
00:20:53,553 --> 00:20:56,231
I've got a pheochromocytoma,
53-year-old male.

490
00:20:56,255 --> 00:20:58,567
How do you suggest I treat him?

491
00:20:58,591 --> 00:21:00,569
Do whatever you think
is medically necessary.

492
00:21:00,593 --> 00:21:02,504
But we won't admit Mr. Fletcher.

493
00:21:02,528 --> 00:21:06,542
Now, if you have any concerns,
take them up with Dr. Romano.

494
00:21:06,566 --> 00:21:08,593
We took Regina
to get cleaned up.

495
00:21:08,617 --> 00:21:11,496
Believe it or not,
a shower can help.

496
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:13,398
She did everything right.

497
00:21:13,422 --> 00:21:15,567
She read that damn
<i>Expecting</i> book every day.

498
00:21:15,591 --> 00:21:18,837
Well, it's important that
she knows it's not her fault.

499
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:20,639
What happened? Did he die?

500
00:21:20,663 --> 00:21:22,107
No, uh, you wait here.

501
00:21:22,131 --> 00:21:24,009
Did they find something
that might help him?

502
00:21:24,033 --> 00:21:25,778
Someone from
Neonatology has to examine

503
00:21:25,802 --> 00:21:28,013
every premature baby
born in the hospital.

504
00:21:28,037 --> 00:21:29,081
They might do something?

505
00:21:29,105 --> 00:21:30,249
Wait here, please.

506
00:21:30,273 --> 00:21:32,017
Note how the thinness
of the fetal tissue

507
00:21:32,041 --> 00:21:34,153
makes thermal
regulation impossible.

508
00:21:34,177 --> 00:21:35,621
The eyes remain closed...

509
00:21:35,645 --> 00:21:36,688
What are you doing?

510
00:21:36,712 --> 00:21:38,157
We heard you had
a micro-preemie.

511
00:21:38,181 --> 00:21:39,241
It's not show-and-tell.

512
00:21:39,265 --> 00:21:41,098
No, it's a teaching hospital.

513
00:21:42,552 --> 00:21:46,298
As you can see, the heart,
limbs and palate are fully formed.

514
00:21:46,322 --> 00:21:47,466
With a transparent skin,

515
00:21:47,490 --> 00:21:49,635
we might even be able
to see the heart beating.

516
00:21:49,659 --> 00:21:51,259
Okay, p... Uh, put him down.

517
00:21:51,728 --> 00:21:52,705
Excuse me?

518
00:21:52,729 --> 00:21:53,722
Put him down.

519
00:21:53,746 --> 00:21:55,724
He is not a science experiment.

520
00:21:55,748 --> 00:21:58,844
No, he isn't. But I need
to examine for anomalies.

521
00:21:58,868 --> 00:21:59,845
You should have called.

522
00:21:59,869 --> 00:22:00,879
Well, you examined him.

523
00:22:00,903 --> 00:22:02,231
Now go. When I'm finished.

524
00:22:02,255 --> 00:22:03,599
The father is standing outside

525
00:22:03,623 --> 00:22:06,652
thinking that you
are saving his baby.

526
00:22:06,676 --> 00:22:08,676
How long would you
like to torture him?

527
00:22:13,999 --> 00:22:16,600
